{{Infobox mathematician |name = Vera W. de Spinadel |image = Vera Martha Winitzky de Spinadel.jpg | birth_date= {{Birth date|df=yes|1929|08|22}} | birth_place= [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]] | death_date= {{Death date and age|df=yes|2017|01|26|1929|08|22}} | death_place= [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]] | nationality = Austrian, Argentine |alma_mater = [[University of Buenos Aires]] |spouse = [[Erico Spinadel]] |children = [[Laura P. Spinadel]], Pablo Spinadel, Irene Spinadel, Andrea Gisela Spinadel }} [[File:Vera Martha Winitzky de Spinadel y Erico Spinadel.jpg|thumb|Vera W de Spinadel & Erico Spinadel]] [[File:IF9 vera Winitzky de spinadel 5.jpg|thumb|Vera Martha Winitzky de Spinadel, writing]]
'''Vera Martha Winitzky de Spinadel''' (August 22, 1929 – January 26, 2017, [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]) was an [[Argentine]] [[mathematician]]. She was the first woman to gain a [[PhD]] in mathematics at the [[University of Buenos Aires]], Argentina, in 1958.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://digital.bl.fcen.uba.ar/Download/Tesis/Tesis_0970_WinitzkydeSpinadel.pdf|title= Doctoral thesis Dr. Vera W. de Spinadel: Dissertation: Theory of Reachable Zones in Bi-dimensional Systems Mathematics Subject Classification: 49—Calculus of variations and optimal control|publisher=University of Buenos Aires, Faculty of Exact and Natural Sciences |accessdate=May 4, 2017 }}</ref> Between 2010 and 2017, she was full [[Emeritus Professor]] in the Faculty of Architecture, Design and Urban Planning of the University of Buenos Aires.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.fadu.uba.ar/categoria/35-institutos-centros-programas|title= Research Locations |publisher=University of Buenos Aires, Faculty of Architecture, Design and Urban Planning |accessdate=May 4, 2017 }}</ref> In 1995, she was named Director of the [[Centre of Mathematics and Design]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://uba.academia.edu/VeraMarthaWinitzkydeSpinadel |title= Reaearcher UBA |publisher=University of Buenos Aires, Faculty of Architecture, Design and Urban Planning |accessdate=May 4, 2017 }}</ref> In April 2005 she inaugurated the Laboratory of Mathematics & Design, University Campus in Buenos Aires.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.ams.org/news/in-memory/in-memory|title= In Memory |publisher= American Mathematic Society |accessdate=May 4, 2017 }}</ref> From 1998 to her death she was the President of the [[International Mathematics and Design Association]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.maydi.org.ar/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20040417042032/http://www.maydi.org.ar/ |dead-url= yes |archive-date= April 17, 2004 |title= International Mathematics & Design Association|publisher= International Mathematics & Design Association |accessdate=May 4, 2017 }}</ref> which organizes international congresses every 3 years and publishes a Journal of Mathematics & Design. She was the author of more than 10 books and published more than 100 research papers.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-ns2013-3076/ |title= Spinadel, Vera W. de|publisher= WorldCat Identities |accessdate=May 4, 2017 }}</ref> Spinadel was a leader in the field of [[Metallic mean]] <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nexusjournal.com/the-nexus-conferences/nexus-1998/119-n1998-spinadel.html|title= Vera W. de Spinadel - The Metallic Means and Design|publisher=Nexus Network Journal |accessdate=May 4, 2017 }}</ref> in the development of the classical [[Golden Ratio]] got wide international recognition.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.mathunion.org/people/gallery/spinadel/|title= Vera W. de Spinadel |publisher=International Mathematics Union|accessdate=May 4, 2017 }}</ref>
